  abstract = {With climate protests on the rise, we ask how do they affect support for pro- and counter-climate movements? We answer this question using evidence from two studies \textendash{} a survey experiment and media content analysis \textendash{} conducted in the Netherlands, a leading country in the green transition. Our experimental findings reveal an asymmetric bias in public support for protests. For the same protest action, public support is higher for counter-climate movements compared to pro- climate ones. This bias is most pronounced among right-leaning individuals, with low education and trust in science and politics. Our content analysis traces the bias back to newspaper reporting. While sentiment about protest groups is balanced in tabloid and broadsheet newspapers, tabloid reporting is more negative about pro- climate movements. These results highlight an important aspect of the backlash against green policies: A bias against pro-climate movements within parts of the public and media.}
